334
36:13.590 --> 36:20.070
So just to be clear about this, we are allowing the
possibility that M equals zero and that gives us an empty sum,

335
36:20.070 --> 36:23.250
which we can interpret as the zero matrix.

336
36:23.250 --> 36:32.130
Now that we have the
concept of a projection at our disposal, we can define a more general
class of quantum measurements known as projective measurements.

337
36:32.130 --> 36:38.850
This isn't the most general
notion of a measurement, but it is significantly more general than standard basis measurements

338
36:38.850 --> 36:44.190
and it's going to be very
helpful to incorporate it into our description
of quantum information.

339
36:44.190 --> 36:54.390
A projective measurement is defined by any set of projections
that satisfies the condition that you see right here, which is that the projections
sum to the identity matrix.

340
36:54.390 --> 37:00.420
Here M can be any
positive integer you like so long as these are all projections and this condition is true,

341
37:00.420 --> 37:04.830
the collection defines a
projective measurement.

342
37:04.830 --> 37:10.590
The measurement described
by such a collection works as follows when you
measure any quantum state Psi.

343
37:10.590 --> 37:16.230
First you get an outcome
between one and M, where M is the number of projections.

344
37:16.230 --> 37:22.590
For each possible outcome, K, the probability to get that outcome is the Euclidean norm
squared of the vector you get

345
37:22.590 --> 37:27.870
by multiplying S by Pi
K, the Kth projection.

346
37:27.870 --> 37:31.440
We can also write this
quantity as you see right here.

347
37:31.440 --> 37:39.480
This equality comes from the relationship between the Euclidean
norm and the inner product together with the fact
that Pi K is a projection.

348
37:39.480 --> 37:47.940
From the second form, together with the condition that we have on these projections, we can see right away, by linearity, that our probabilities
will always sum to one,

349
37:47.940 --> 37:52.740
keeping in mind that Psi
has to be a unit vector.

350
37:52.740 --> 38:03.930
And second, assuming that
we get the outcome, K, the state of the system
collapses to the quantum state we get by normalizing whatever
vector we got by projecting.

351
38:03.930 --> 38:09.960
We'll take a look at some
examples in just a moment, but before we do that, let me mention that we don't actually need

352
38:09.960 --> 38:18.030
to number the possible
outcomes from one to M. We can choose whatever names or symbols we want for the outcomes.

353
38:18.030 --> 38:24.060
In particular, if we have a collection of projections that are labeled with symbols
from sum set gamma say,

354
38:24.060 --> 38:30.960
and they satisfy the
same condition as before, which is that they sum
to the identity matrix, then we have a projective measurement

355
38:30.960 --> 38:34.590
that works in exactly
the same way as before.

356
38:34.590 --> 38:46.380
The only only difference here is that we're allowing
the measurement outcomes to be elements of this set gamma as opposed to the integers from one to M.

357
38:46.380 --> 38:55.500
For our first example of
a projective measurement, let's observe that
standard basis measurements are projective measurements.

358
38:55.500 --> 39:04.230
In this case the set of
outcomes of the measurement is the same as the set of classical states of whatever system is being measured.

359
39:04.230 --> 39:11.160
And the set of projections
that describes the measurement is this collection right here, assuming that sigma is
the classical state set

360
39:11.160 --> 39:21.630
of our system. These are all projections
and if we sum them up, we get the identity matrix, so it's a valid projective measurement

361
39:21.630 --> 39:30.420
To see how this works in
a little bit more detail, let's suppose that we
have some arbitrary state that's written in the form
that you see right here.

362
39:30.420 --> 39:38.490
The probability for the
measurement to yield the outcome A, according to the description
from a moment ago, is this value right here,

363
39:38.490 --> 39:45.300
which is equal to the
absolute value squared of the corresponding
entry of the vector Psi, which is what we expect.

364
39:45.300 --> 39:53.520
Conditioned on the outcome being A, the state of the system becomes this, again, according to the
description from a moment ago.

365
39:53.520 --> 39:57.810
If we simplify, we don't
quite get the state we expect, which is Ket A.

366
39:57.810 --> 40:04.410
Instead we get Ket A
multiplied by a scaler, and specifically, this is a scaler having
absolute value equal to one,

367
40:04.410 --> 40:08.340
so it's a complex number
on the unit circle.

368
40:08.340 --> 40:16.080
This is called a global phase and we'll discuss global phases shortly, but for now in short, this
state is equivalent to Ket A.

369
40:16.080 --> 40:23.280
This global phase doesn't
actually have any significance at all and we'll see why
when we get to the discussion of global phases.

370
40:23.280 --> 40:30.030
So (unclear) this issue of global phases, which we'll talk about in just a moment, we see that standard basis measurements

371
40:30.030 --> 40:36.930
are in fact projective measurements. For another example, which is really an extension
of the previous example,

372
40:36.930 --> 40:44.310
if we perform a standard basis
measurement on a system X and we do nothing to a system Y, just like we talked about
in the previous lesson,

373
40:44.310 --> 40:47.550
it's completely equivalent
to measuring the system X, Y.

374
40:47.550 --> 40:51.180
With this projective
measurement right here.

375
40:51.180 --> 40:57.540
We have these projections corresponding to the classical states of X and we're tensoring with the identity on Y

376
40:57.540 --> 41:02.550
which reflects the fact that
we're not doing anything to Y.

377
41:02.550 --> 41:10.590
The description for how
projective measurements work in general tells us
what happens in this example, and I'll leave it to you to
check that this is in fact

378
41:10.590 --> 41:14.970
completely equivalent to what we discussed in the previous lesson.

379
41:14.970 --> 41:25.860
This is all very nice because this projective
measurement description is cleaner in a way and we see that it fits into
this more general picture.

